    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Working Families, Going Without</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Rev John Bucki letter on Sept 13 article holds working New York City families are increasingly turning to emergency food programs because living expenses far outstrip low-wage incomes</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The study showing that living expenses in New York City far outstrip low-wage incomes (news article, Sept. 13) raises a question: How have working New Yorkers been surviving? The answer is no secret to those of us who run the soup kitchens and food pantries.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The study showing that living expenses in New York City far outstrip low-wage incomes (news article, Sept. 13) raises a question: How have working New Yorkers been surviving? The answer is no secret to those of us who run the soup kitchens and food pantries.</p>
        <p>Despite a robust economy, more and more working families are coming to emergency food programs. Unfortunately, most programs can't feed everyone seeking help. The solution is not more programs. We need an increase in the minimum wage, coupled with job-creation programs to develop living-wage jobs for  low-skilled workers, effective job training and education, and affordable housing.</p>
        <p>(Rev.) JOHN BUCKI  New York, Sept. 13, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is director of the St. Francis Xavier Welcome Table and chairman of the New York City Coalition Against Hunger.</p>
      </block>
